th respect to \\(\\tau\\); that is, split \\(m\\) into parts absolutely continuous and singular with respect to \\(\\tau\\), and compute the Radon–Nikodym derivative \\(dm/d\\tau\\) on the absolutely continuous part.\n\n**WHY IT IS HARD**  \nThe pushforward \\(\\tau\\) is supported on the interval \\([0,1]\\) but its density with respect to one-dimensional Lebesgue measure is not given explicitly; we must integrate out the \\(y\\)-variable to find \\(\\tau\\). Students often forget that projections can collapse sets of \\(\\mu\\)-measure zero into sets of positive \\(\\tau\\)-measure, so one has to carefully compute \\(\\tau(E)=\\mu(P^{-1}(E))\\) for measurable \\(E\\subset\\mathbb{R}\\). The real work is to understand how much mass \\(\\tau\\) assigns to subsets of \\([0,1]\\) (it turns out \\(\\tau\\) has density \\(2x\\) on \\([0,1]\\)) and to identify whether Lebesgue measure has a singular part (it does: outside \\([0,1]\\), \\(m\\) is singular w.r.t. \\(\\tau\\)). The prerequisites are comfort with pushforward measures, the Fubini–Tonelli theorem for computing densities, and the Lebesgue decomposition theorem.", :propose "**THE KEY INSIGHT**  \nCompute the pushforward measure explicitly: for any \\(E\\subset\\mathbb{R}\\),\n\\[\n\\tau(E)=\\mu(P^{-1}(E))=\\int_{P^{-1}(E)} g(x,y)\\,dx\\,dy\n= \\int_E \\left(\\int_0^{\\min(x,1)} 2\\,dy\\right)dx = \\int_E 2\\min(x,1)\\,dx.\n\\]\nHence \\(\\tau\\) has density \\(2x\\) on \\([0,1]\\) and zero outside. Therefore \\(m\\) and \\(\\tau\\) are mutually absolutely continuous on \\([0,1]\\), while \\(m\\) is singular with respect to \\(\\tau\\) on \\((-\\infty,0)\\cup(1,\\infty)\\). The Lebesgue decomposition is \\(m = m_{\\mathrm{ac}} + m_{\\mathrm{s}}\\), with \\(m_{\\mathrm{ac}}\\) supported on \\([0,1]\\) and having Radon–Nikodym derivative \\(dm_{\\mathrm{ac}}/d\\tau = 1/(2x)\\) on \\((0,1]\\); on the singular part \\((-\\infty,0)\\cup(1,\\infty)\\), the derivative is irrelevant because \\(\\tau\\) vanishes there.\n\n**THE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS**  \nA common misstep is to assume \\(\\tau\\) is just Lebesgue measure on \\([0,1]\\) and to guess that the Radon–Nikodym derivative is \\(1\\). This ignores how the density \\(g\\) depends on \\(x\\): when pushing forward via \\(P\\), the \\(y\\)-integral contributes a factor of \\(x\\), so \\(\\tau\\) is not uniform on \\([0,1]\\). Another dead end is to try to apply the Lebesgue decomposition without explicitly computing \\(\\tau\\); without knowing the density of \\(\\tau\\), one cannot determine the absolute-continuous or singular parts. The structural obstacle is that pushforward measures must be computed through the change-of-variables integral, not guessed; only after finding \\(\\tau(E)=\\int_E 2x\\,dx\\) can the decomposition and Radon–Nikodym derivative be read off.", :execute "Stage 1 — THE CLEAN PROOF\n--------------------------------\n\n\\(\\mu\\) is supported on the triangle \\(0\\le y\\le x\\le1\\). For measurable \\(E\\subset\\mathbb{R}\\),\n\\[\n\\tau(E)=\\mu(P^{-1}(E))=\\int_{P^{-1}(E)} g(x,y)\\,dx\\,dy\n=\\int_E\\Bigl(\\int_{0}^{\\min(x,1)}2\\,dy\\Bigr)dx\n=\\int_E 2\\min(x,1)\\,dx.\n\\]\nHence \\(\\tau\\) is supported on \\([0,1]\\) with density \\(2x\\) relative to Lebesgue measure \\(m\\). Therefore \\(m\\) decomposes as \\(m=m_{\\mathrm{ac}}+m_{\\mathrm{s}}\\), where \\(m_{\\mathrm{ac}}\\) is \\(m\\) restricted to \\([0,1]\\) (absolutely continuous with respect to \\(\\tau\\)) and \\(m_{\\mathrm{s}}\\) is \\(m\\) restricted to \\((-\\infty,0)\\cup(1,\\infty)\\) (singular w.r.t. \\(\\tau\\)). On \\((0,1]\\),\n\\[\n\\frac{dm_{\\mathrm{ac}}}{d\\tau}(x)=\\frac{1}{2x},\n\\]\nand outside \\((0,1]\\) the derivative is irrelevant because \\(\\tau\\) vanishes there. Thus \\(m_{\\mathrm{ac}}\\) has density \\(1/(2x)\\) relative to \\(\\tau\\) on \\((0,1]\\), and \\(m_{\\mathrm{s}}\\) is concentrated on \\((-\\infty,0)\\cup(1,\\infty)\\).\n\n---\n\nStage 2 — LEMMA DEPENDENCY GRAPH\n--------------------------------\n\n1.